            <!-- Theory & explanation -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>What is Pecking Order Theory?</h2>
              <p>
                Pecking order theory (Myers &amp; Majluf, 1984) explains how
                firms choose among
                <strong>internal funds</strong>, <strong>debt</strong>, and
                <strong>equity</strong> when financing new investments. Because
                of information asymmetry and issuance costs, managers follow a
                hierarchy:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Internal funds first</strong> (retained earnings,
                  excess cash)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Then debt</strong> (bank loans, bonds)</li>
                <li><strong>Equity last</strong> (new share issues)</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The key idea is that issuing equity can signal that managers
                think the firm is overvalued, so equity is relatively
                “expensive” compared to internal funds and debt.
              </p>

              <h3>Basic logic of the calculator</h3>
              <p>The tool implements this hierarchy in three steps:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Use internal funds:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Internal used} = \min(\text{Investment},
                  \text{Internal funds}) \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Add debt (subject to limits):</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Remaining need: \[ \text{Need}_1 = \text{Investment} -
                  \text{Internal used} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Maximum debt allowed by target leverage: \[
                  D_{\max}^{\text{target}} = \text{Max D/E} \times
                  (\text{Equity}_{\text{current}} + \text{New equity}) \] In
                  practice, we approximate the incremental capacity as: \[
                  \Delta D_{\max} \approx \text{Max D/E} \times
                  \text{Equity}_{\text{current}} - \text{Debt}_{\text{current}}
                  \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Maximum new debt: \[ \text{New debt}_{\max} = \max(0,
                  \min(\Delta D_{\max}, \text{Hard debt cap})) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Debt used: \[ \text{Debt used} = \min(\text{Need}_1, \text{New
                  debt}_{\max}) \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 3 – Use equity as last resort:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Remaining need: \[ \text{Need}_2 = \text{Need}_1 - \text{Debt
                  used} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  If equity is allowed: \[ \text{Equity used} = \text{Need}_2 \]
                  Otherwise, the model reports a <strong>funding gap</strong>.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Issue costs and effective financing</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator also reports the
                <strong>issue cost burden</strong> of debt and equity. If you
                raise an amount \( X \) with an issue cost rate \( c \), the net
                proceeds are:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>\[ \text{Net proceeds} = X \times (1 - c) \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Under pecking order theory, internal funds have effectively zero
                issue cost, debt has moderate cost, and equity has the highest
                cost and strongest signaling effect.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Suppose a firm has:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Required investment: \$100,000</li>
                <li>Internal funds: \$40,000</li>
                <li>Current debt: \$200,000</li>
                <li>Current equity: \$300,000</li>
                <li>Max D/E: 1.0</li>
                <li>Hard cap on new debt: \$80,000</li>
              </ul>
              <p>The calculator will:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Use \$40,000 of internal funds → remaining need = \$60,000
                </li>
                <li>
                  Target D/E = 1.0 implies max debt ≈ \$300,000. With current
                  debt \$200,000, incremental capacity ≈ \$100,000, but the hard
                  cap is \$80,000, so new debt ≤ \$80,000.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Remaining need is \$60,000, so it uses \$60,000 of new debt
                  (within the \$80,000 cap).
                </li>
                <li>No equity is needed; funding gap is \$0.</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Post-financing, debt is \$260,000 and equity is still \$300,000,
                so D/E ≈ 0.87, below the 1.0 limit.
              </p>

              <h2>When is pecking order theory most relevant?</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Firms with
                  <strong>significant information asymmetry</strong> between
                  insiders and outside investors
                </li>
                <li>
                  Companies with <strong>volatile earnings</strong> or
                  hard-to-value growth options
                </li>
                <li>
                  Situations where
                  <strong>equity issuance is interpreted negatively</strong> by
                  the market
                </li>
                <li>
                  Privately held firms that prefer to avoid ownership dilution
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Limitations</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Real-world firms often follow a
                  <strong>hybrid policy</strong>: a long-run target leverage
                  plus a short-run pecking order.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Debt capacity is constrained by
                  <strong>covenants, ratings, and risk appetite</strong>, not
                  just a simple D/E ratio.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The theory is <strong>descriptive</strong> (explains behavior)
                  rather than strictly normative (what firms “should” do).
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

