                Pecking Order Theory – FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is pecking order theory in corporate finance?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Pecking order theory states that firms prefer to finance new
                    investments first with internal funds, then with debt, and
                    only as a last resort with new equity. The ranking is driven
                    by information asymmetry and issuance costs: internal funds
                    are cheapest and least visible, debt is next, and equity is
                    most expensive and sends the strongest signal to the market.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How does this calculator apply pecking order theory?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The calculator takes your investment need, internal funds,
                    current debt and equity, and leverage constraints. It then
                    allocates financing in three steps: internal funds, then new
                    debt up to your limits, and finally equity if allowed. It
                    also shows the resulting D/E ratio and any funding gap if
                    constraints prevent full financing.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Should I use book or market values for debt and equity?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For capital structure analysis,
                    <strong>market values</strong> are usually preferred,
                    because they reflect current investor expectations. However,
                    many covenants and internal policies are expressed in terms
                    of <strong>book values</strong>. Use the measure that is
                    most relevant for your decision, but be consistent across
                    inputs.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is pecking order theory always better than target capital
                    structure?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    No. Target capital structure focuses on minimizing the
                    long-run cost of capital and balancing tax shields against
                    financial distress costs. Pecking order theory focuses on
                    information asymmetry and issuance costs. Many firms use a
                    <strong>hybrid approach</strong>: they maintain a leverage
                    range but still prefer internal funds over external
                    financing in the short run.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I use this tool for startups or highly leveraged firms?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    You can, but interpret results carefully. Startups often
                    have limited internal funds and rely heavily on equity, so
                    the classic pecking order may not hold. Highly leveraged
                    firms may face binding covenants or rating constraints that
                    reduce their practical debt capacity below what a simple D/E
                    limit suggests. Use the calculator as a
                    <strong>scenario tool</strong>, not as a binding rule.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
